\pard\ltrpar\keepn\s3\sb240\sa60 Shareholders and management\par
\pard\ltrpar\nowidctlpar\sl360\slmult1 The separation of ownership and control in most modern corporations\rquote  causes a conflict of interest between the personal interest of appointed managers (agent) and the interests of the owners of the firms (principals).this conflict is known as the \b agency conflict.\par
\b0 The following are some decisions by managers which would result in a conflict with shareholders:\par
\pard{\pntext\f0 1.\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlbody\pnf0\pnindent360\pnstart1\pndec{\pntxta.}}
\ltrpar\nowidctlpar\fi-360\li720\sl360\slmult1\tx720 Managers may use corporate resources for personal use.\par
\pard{\pntext\f0 2.\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlbody\pnf0\pnindent360\pnstart2\pndec{\pntxta.}}
\ltrpar\nowidctlpar\fi-360\li720\sl360\slmult1\tx720 Managers may award themselves hefty pay rises\par
\pard{\pntext\f0 3.\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlbody\pnf0\pnindent360\pnstart3\pndec{\pntxta.}}
\ltrpar\nowidctlpar\fi-360\li720\sl360\slmult1\tx720 Managers may organize mergers which are intended for their benefit only and not for the benefit of shareholders.\par
\pard{\pntext\f0 4.\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlbody\pnf0\pnindent360\pnstart4\pndec{\pntxta.}}
\ltrpar\nowidctlpar\fi-360\li720\sl360\slmult1\tx720 Managers may take holidays and spend huge sums of company money.\par
\pard{\pntext\f0 5.\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlbody\pnf0\pnindent360\pnstart5\pndec{\pntxta.}}
\ltrpar\nowidctlpar\fi-360\li720\sl360\slmult1\tx720 Managers may use confidential information for their benefit(insider trading)\par
\pard\ltrpar\nowidctlpar\sl360\slmult1\par
\b Resolution of conflict\par
\i 1. Performance based remuneration\par
\b0\i0 This will involve remunerating managers for actions they take that maximize shareholders wealth. The remuneration scheme should be restructured in order to enhance the harmonization of the interest of shareholders with those of management. Managers could be given bonuses, commissions for superior performance in certain periods.\par
\b\i 2. Incurring agency costs\par
\b0\i0 Agency costs refer to costs incurred by shareholders in trying to control management behavior and actions and therefore minimize agency conflicts.\par
These costs include:\par
\ul a) Monitoring costs.\ulnone  They arise as a result of mechanisms put in place to ensure interests of shareholders are met. They include cost of hiring external auditors, bonding assurance which is insurance taken out where the firm is compensated if manager commits an infringement, internal control system implementation.\par
\ul b) Opportunity costs\ulnone  which are incurred either because of the benefit foregone from not investing in a riskier but more profitable investment or in the due to the delay in decision making as procedures have to be followed(hence, a timely decision will not be made)\par
\ul c) Restructuring costs\ulnone  are those costs incurred in changing or altering an organizations structure so as to prevent undesirable management activities. \par
\pard\ltrpar\sa200\sl360\slmult1\qj\ul d)\b  \b0 Board of directors\ulnone - a properly constituted board plays the oversight role on management for the shareholders.\par
\pard\ltrpar\nowidctlpar\sl360\slmult1\par
\b\i 3. Threat of corporate takeover\par
\b0\i0 When management of a firm under performs this result in the shares of that firm being undervalued there is the threat of a hostile takeover. This threat acts to force managers to perform since should the firm be taken over they will be replaced.\par
\b\i 4. Shareholders intervention\par
\b0\i0 The shareholders as owners of the company have a right to vote. Hence, during the company\rquote s AGM the shareholders can unite to form a bloc that will vote as one for or against decisions by managers that hurt the company. This voting power can be exercised even when voting for directors. Shareholders could demand for an independent board of directors.\par
\b\i 5. Legal protection\par
\b0\i0  The companies act and bodies such as the capital markets authority have played their role in ensuring trying to minimize the agency conflict. Under the companies act, management and board of directors owe a duty of care to shareholders and as such can face legal liability for their acts of omission or commission that are in conflict with shareholders interests. The capital market authority also has corporate governance guidelines.\par
\b\i 6. Use of corporate governance principles\b0\i0  which specify the manner in which organizations are controlled and managed. The duties and rights of all stakeholders are outlined.\par
\b\i 7. Stock option schemes\b0\i0  for managers could be introduced. These entitle a manager to purchase from the company a specified number of common shares at a price below market price over duration.  The incentive for managers to look at shareholders interests and not their own is that, if they deliver and the company\rquote s share price appreciates in the stock market then they will make a profit from the sale.\par
\b\i 8. Labour market actions\b0\i0  such as hiring tried and tested professional managers and firing poor performers could be used. The concept of 'head hunting' is fast catching on in Kenya as a way of getting the best professional managers and executives in the market but at a fee of course. \par
\par
\pard\ltrpar\keepn\s3\sb240\sa60\b  \b0 Shareholders vs. creditors\par
\pard\ltrpar\nowidctlpar\sl360\slmult1 In this relationship the shareholders (agent) are expected to manage the credit funds provided by the creditors (principal). The shareholders manage these funds through management.\b\par
\b0 Debt providers/creditors are those who provide loan and credit facilities to the firm. They do this after gauging the riskiness of the firm.\par
The following actions by shareholders through management could lead to a conflict between them and creditors\par
\b 1. Shareholders could invest in very risky projects\par
\b0 The management under the directive of the shareholders may undertake highly risky investments than those anticipated by the providers of long term debt finance. The creditors would not be interested in highly risky projects because they stand to lose their funds when the investments collapse. Even if the risky projects succeed they would not benefit because they only get a fixed rate of return.\par
\b 2. The dividend payments to shareholders could be very high\par
\b0 An increase in the dividend rate in most cases is financed by a decrease in investments. This in turn reduces the value of bonds. If the firm is liquidating and it pays a liquidating dividend to its shareholders, the providers of capital could be left with worthless claims.\par
3. Default on interest payments to bondholders\par
4. Shareholders could organize mergers which are not beneficial to creditors\par
5. Shareholders could acquire additional debt that increases the financial risk of the firm\par
6. Manipulation of financial statements so as to mislead creditors\par
7. Shareholders could dispose of assets which are security for the credit given\par
8. Under investments \par
The shareholders may invest in projects with a negative net present value. \par
9. The shareholders may adopt an aggressive management of working capital. This may bring conflicts in liquidity position of the firm and would not be in the interest of the debt holders \par
\par
 \par
\b Resolution of this conflict\par
\i 1. Restrictive covenants\b0\i0 - these are agreements entered into between the firm and the creditors to protect the creditor\rquote s interests.\par
These covenants may provide restrictions/control over:\par
\pard{\pntext\f0 i.\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlbody\pnf0\pnindent360\pnstart1\pnlcrm{\pntxta.}}
\ltrpar\nowidctlpar\fi-360\li720\sl360\slmult1 Asset based covenants- These states that the minimum asset base to be maintained by the firm.\par
\pard{\pntext\f0 ii.\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlbody\pnf0\pnindent360\pnstart2\pnlcrm{\pntxta.}}
\ltrpar\nowidctlpar\fi-360\li720\sl360\slmult1 Liability based covenant- This limits the firm\rquote s ability to incur more debt.\par
\pard{\pntext\f0 iii.\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlbody\pnf0\pnindent360\pnstart3\pnlcrm{\pntxta.}}
\ltrpar\nowidctlpar\fi-360\li720\sl360\slmult1 Cashflow based covenant- States minimum working capital to be held by the firm. This may restrict the amount of dividends to be paid in future.\par
