\pard\ltrpar\keepn\s2\sb240\sa60\sl276\slmult1\b\i Types\i0  \i of\i0  \i Business\i0  \i Organizations\i0  \par
\pard\ltrpar\sa200\sl360\slmult1\qj\b0 The three basic forms of business organizations are a proprietorship, a partnership and a corporation (limited liability companies)\par
\b Sole Proprietorship \par
\b0 A proprietorship is an organization in which a single person owns the business, holds title to all the assets and is personally responsible for all liabilities. The main virtue of a proprietorship is that it can be easily established and is subject to minimum government regulation and supervision. The proprietorship\rquote s shortcomings include the owner\rquote s unlimited liability for the all business debts, the limitations in raising capital, and the difficulty in transferring ownership. \par
The proprietorship pays no separate income taxes.  Rather the income or losses from the proprietorship are included on the owner\rquote s personal tax return.  \par
\pard\ltrpar\keepn\s2\sb240\sa60\sl360\slmult1\b Partnership \par
\pard\ltrpar\sa200\sl360\slmult1\qj\b0 A partnership is similar to a proprietorship, except that it is owned by two or more persons. The profit of the partnership is taxed on the individual partners after sharing. \par
\pard\ltrpar\sl360\slmult1\qj A potential advantage of a partnership compared to a proprietorship is that a greater amount of capital can be raised. \par
\pard\ltrpar\sa200\sl360\slmult1\qj In a \i genera\i0 l partnership each partner is personally responsible for the obligations of the business. A formal agreement (partnership deed) is necessary to set forth the privileges and duties of each partner, the distribution of profits, capital contributions, procedures for admitting new partners and modalities of reconstitutions of the partners in the event of death or withdrawal of a partner. \par
In a limited partnership, limited partners contribute capital and their liability is confined to that amount of capital. There must be however, at least one general partner in the partnership who manages the firm and his liability is unlimited. \par
\b Types of partners\par
\pard{\pntext\f0 1.\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlbody\pnf0\pnindent360\pnstart1\pndec{\pntxta.}}
\ltrpar\fi-360\li720\sa200\sl360\slmult1\qj\b0 General partners- they have an unlimited liability and take active participation the running of the business.\par
\pard{\pntext\f0 2.\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlbody\pnf0\pnindent360\pnstart2\pndec{\pntxta.}}
\ltrpar\fi-360\li720\sa200\sl360\slmult1\qj Limited partners- they have a limited liability and do not take part in the management of the partnerships.\par
\pard{\pntext\f0 3.\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlbody\pnf0\pnindent360\pnstart3\pndec{\pntxta.}}
\ltrpar\fi-360\li720\sa200\sl360\slmult1\qj Sleeping partners- they have no active role, but they contribute in the capital of the business and will participate in the profits although at a lower proportion. \par
\pard\ltrpar\sa200\sl360\slmult1\qj\b Joint stock company/ Corporation \par
\b0 Joint stock companies/Corporation A corporation is an \ldblquote artificial entity\rdblquote  created by law. A corporation is empowered to own assets, to incur liabilities, engage in certain specified activities, and to sue and be sued. The principal features of this form of business organization are that the owner\rquote s liability is limited; there is ease of transfer of ownership through sale of shares; the corporation has unlimited life apart from its owners and; the corporation has the ability to raise large amounts of capital. \par
A possible disadvantage is that corporation profits are subject to double taxation. A minor disadvantage is the difficulties and expenses encountered in the formation. Corporation are owned by shareholders whose ownership is evidenced by ordinary stocks shareholders expect earn a return by receiving a dividend or gain decisions. \par
Corporations are formed under the provisions of the Companies Act (CAP486). A Board of Directors, elected by the owners, has ultimate authority in guiding the corporate affairs and in making strategic policy decisions. The directors appoint the executive officers (often referred to as management) of the company, who run the company on a day-to-day basis and implement the policies established by the directors.\cf2  The chief executive officer (CEO) is responsible for managing day-to-day operations and carrying out the policies established by the board. The CEO is required to report periodically \i to\i0  the firm's directors.\par
