\pard\ltrpar\keepn\s1 Return \par
\pard\ltrpar\sa200 The return on an asset is the total gain or loss experienced on an investment over a given period of time.  It is commonly measured as the change in value plus any cash distribution during the period, expressed as a percentage of the beginning of the period investment value.\par
The following equation captures the essence of this value.\tab\tab\tab\par
\pard\ltrpar\fi720\li1440\sa200\b  k\sub t\nosupersub  = (C\sub t\nosupersub  + [P\sub t\nosupersub  \endash  P\sub t-1\nosupersub ])/ P\sub t-1         \tab\tab\nosupersub (3.1)\par
\pard\ltrpar\sa200\b0 Where k\sub t\nosupersub   =  actual, expected, or required rate of return during period t\par
\tab P\sub t\nosupersub    =  Price (value) of asset at time t\par
\tab P\sub t-1\nosupersub  = Price value of asset at time t-1\par
\tab C\sub t\nosupersub   = Cash (flow) received from the asset investment in the time period t-1  to t.\par
t may be one day, 10 years or one year.  When it is one year\b  k\sub t\nosupersub\b0  represents an annual rate of return. The return could be positive or negative in the event of a loss.\par
