\pard\ltrpar\keepn\s1 Risk Profile.\par
\pard\ltrpar\sa200 The three basic risk preference behaviors among managers are \endash  risk-aversion, risk-indifference and risk-seeking.\par
\b Risk-indifference\b0 , is the attitude toward risk in which no change in return would be required for an increment risk\par
\b Risk-aversion \b0 is the attitude toward risk in which an increased return would be required for an increase in risk.\par
\b Risk seeking \b0 is the attitude toward risk in which a decreased return would be accepted for an increase in risk. \par
                                 \ul\b Graphically illustrates the three risk preferences.\par
\ulnone\b0\par
\par
\pard\ltrpar\sb240\sa200 Most managers and investors are risk-averse; for an increase in risk they require an, increase in returns. Consequently, managers and investors tend to be conservative rather than aggressive in accepting risk. Accordingly, unless specified otherwise, a risk adverse financial behavior will be assumed. \par
