\pard\ltrpar\keepn\s2\sb240\sa60\sl276\slmult1\b Financial forecasting.\par
\pard\ltrpar\nowidctlpar\li360\sl360\slmult1\b0 It involves determining the future financial requirements of the firm. This requires financial planning using budgets.\par
\b  Importance of financial forecasting.\par
\pard{\pntext\f14\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf14\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\ltrpar\nowidctlpar\fi-720\li1080\sl360\slmult1\b0 Facilitates financial planning i.e. determination of cash surplus or deficit that are likely to occur in future.\par
{\pntext\f14\'B7\tab}Facilitates control of expenditure so as to minimize wastage of financial resources.\par
{\pntext\f14\'B7\tab}Forecasting using targets and budgets acts as a motivation to employees who aim at achieving targets set\b\par
\pard\ltrpar\nowidctlpar\li360\sl360\slmult1\par
\pard\ltrpar\keepn\s3\sb240\sa60\b0 Methods used in financial forecasting.\par
\pard\ltrpar\nowidctlpar\li360\sl360\slmult1  1. Use of cash budgets \par
A cash budget is a financial statement indicating sources of revenue, the expected expenditure and any anticipated cash deficit/ surplus.\par
2. Regression analysis\par
It is a statistical method which involves identification of dependent and independent variables to form a regression equation y=a + bx on which forecasting is based.\par
3. Percentage of sales method\par
 One of the items that have a great influence on forecasting is sales. Hence items in the balance sheet which re related to sales are expressed as a percentage of sales. The following steps are involved:\par
\par
a) Identify balance sheet items that are directly related to sales\par
  -net fixed assets-say acquisition of new machinery which increase production hence increase sales.\par
  -Current assets-an increase in sales due to increased in stock raw materials, work in progress and finished goods. Increased credit sales will increase debtors while more cash will be required to buy more raw materials in cash.\par
  -current liabilities-increased sales will lead to purchase of more raw materials.\par
  -Retained earnings-this will increase with sales if and only if, the firm is operating at a profit.\par
Long term capital items such as ordinary share capital, preference share capital and debentures are not directly impacted by an increase in sales as they are used to finance long term projects. \par
\par
b) Express the above identified items as a percentage of sales i.e determine the relationship between the item and current sales.\par
c) Determine the increase in total assets as a result of increase in sales.\par
\par
d) Determine total increase in spontaneous sources of finance (current liabilities) and increase in retained earnings.\par
Retained earnings = net profit - dividend paid\par
Net profit margin = \ul Net profit\par
\ulnone                                     Sales\par
Therefore net profit = net profit margin x sales\par
\b\par
\b0 e) Get the external financing needed which is the difference between increase in users of funds(c) and (d)\par
\par
f) Prepare the proforma financial statements- these are projected statements at the end of the forecasting period.\par
Note: information could be given which necessitates the determination of forecast sales, this will be determined using the following formula:\par
\par
                S\sub n\nosupersub  =S\sub o\nosupersub (1+ g)\super n\nosupersub\par
Where:    S\sub n\nosupersub  = sales n years from now\par
           S\sub o\nosupersub =current sales\par
           g=growth rate\par
           n= forecasting period\par
\b Assumptions of percentage of sales method.\par
\pard{\pntext\f14\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf14\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\ltrpar\nowidctlpar\fi-720\li1080\sl360\slmult1\b0 The fundamental assumption is that there's no inflation in the economy .i.e. the increase in sales is caused by an increase production and not increase in selling price.\par
{\pntext\f14\'B7\tab}The firm is operating at full capacity. hence, the increase in production will require an increase infixed assets\par
{\pntext\f14\'B7\tab}The capital remains constant during the forecasting  period i.e. no issue of ordinary or preference shares and debentures\par
{\pntext\f14\'B7\tab}That the relationship between the balance sheet items and sales remains the same during the forecasting period.\par
{\pntext\f14\'B7\tab}The net profit margin will be achieved and shall remain constant during the forecasting period\b\par
\pard\ltrpar\s6\sb240\sa60\sl360\slmult1 Comparisons in Financial Analysis\par
\pard\ltrpar\sa200\sl360\slmult1\b0 The figures in the financial statements are rarely significant\b  \b0 or important in themselves. It is\b\i  \b0\i0 their relationships to other quantities, amounts and the direction\b  \b0 of change from one point in time to another point in time that\b  \b0 is of importance. It is only through comparison of data that one can gain insight and make intelligent judgments. Analysis thus involves establishing significant relationships that point to changes as well as trends. We thus can apply the ratios above in comparison of financial statements.\par
The two comparisons widely used for analytical purpose involve trend and cross-sectional analyses.\par
\pard\ltrpar\s6\sb240\sa60\sl360\slmult1\b Trend Analysis\par
\pard\ltrpar\sa200\sl360\slmult1\b0 This is also known as time series analysis, horizontal analysis\b  \b0 or temporally analysis. It involves the comparison of the present performance with the result of previous periods for the same enterprise. Trend analysis is therefore usually employed when financial data is available for three or more periods. Developing trends can be seen by using multiyear comparisons and knowledge of these trends can assist in controlling current operations and planning for the future. It can be carried out by computing percentages for the element of the financial statement that is under observation. Trend percentage analysis states several years' financial data in terms of a base year, which is set to be equal to 100%.\par
\pard\ltrpar\sb180\sa200\sl360\slmult1 In conducting trend analysis the following need to\b  \b0 be taken into account:\par
(i)    \tab Accounting principles and policies employed in the preparation of financial\par
\pard\ltrpar\fi500\li280\sa200\sl360\slmult1 Statement must be followed consistently for the periods for which an analysis is\par
\pard\ltrpar\fi500\li280\ri1000\sa200\sl360\slmult1 Being made to allow comparability.\par
\pard{\pntext\f0 (ii)\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlbody\pnf0\pnindent360\pnstart2\pnlcrm{\pntxtb(}{\pntxta)}}
\ltrpar\fi-720\li960\ri1000\sl360\slmult1\tx960 The base year selected must be normal and a representative year.\par
\pard{\pntext\f0 (iii)\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlbody\pnf0\pnindent360\pnstart3\pnlcrm{\pntxtb(}{\pntxta)}}
\ltrpar\fi-720\li960\ri1000\sl360\slmult1\tx960 Trend percentages should be calculated only for these items, which have logical relationship.\par
\pard{\pntext\f0 (iv)\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlbody\pnf0\pnindent360\pnstart4\pnlcrm{\pntxtb(}{\pntxta)}}
\ltrpar\fi-720\li960\ri1000\sl360\slmult1\tx960 Trend percentages should be carefully studied after considering the absolute figures; otherwise they may lead to misleading conclusions.\par
\pard{\pntext\f0 (v)\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlbody\pnf0\pnindent360\pnstart5\pnlcrm{\pntxtb(}{\pntxta)}}
\ltrpar\fi-720\li960\ri1000\sl360\slmult1\tx960 To make meaningful comparisons, trend percentage should be adjusted in light of price changes to the base year.\par
