\ltrpar\fi-360\li360\sl360\slmult1\qj\tx360 Apply the mathematics of finance to accumulate a future sum, preparing loan amortization schedules, and determining interest or growth rates. \par
\pard\ltrpar\sa200\sl360\slmult1\qj\par
\pard\ltrpar\nowidctlpar\sl360\slmult1\b\par
\pard\ltrpar\keepn\s2\sb240\sa60\sl276\slmult1 Introduction .\par
\pard\ltrpar\sa200\sl360\slmult1\qj\b0 A shilling today is worth more than a shilling tomorrow. An individual would thus prefer to receive money now rather than that same amount later. A shilling in ones possession today is more valuable than a shilling to be received in future because, first, the shilling in hand can be put to immediate productive use, and, secondly, a shilling in hand is free from the uncertainties of future expectations (It is a \i sure shilling)\i0 .\par
\pard\ltrpar\sl360\slmult1\qj Financial values and decisions can be assessed by using either future value (FV) or present value (PV) techniques. These techniques result in the same decisions, but adopt different approaches to the decision. \par
\pard\ltrpar\sa200\sl360\slmult1\qj\b Future value techniques\b0  \par
Measure cash flow at the some future point in time \endash  typically at the end of a projects life. The \b Future Value (FV),\b0  or terminal value, is the value at some time in future of a present sum of money, or a series of payments or receipts. In other words the FV refers to the amount of money an investment will grow to over some period of time at some given interest rate.  FV techniques use \b compounding\b0  to find the future value of each cash flow at the given future date and the sums those values to find the value of cash flows.\par
\b Present value techniques\b0  \par
Measure each cash flows at the start of a projects life (time zero).The \b Present Value (PV)\b0  is the current value of a future amount of money, or a series of future payments or receipts. Present value is just like cash in hand today. PV techniques use \b discounting\b0  to find the PV of each cash flow at time zero and then sums these values to find the total value of the cash flows. \par
Although FV and PV techniques result in the same decisions, since financial managers make decisions in the present, they tend to rely primarily on PV techniques.\par
\pard\ltrpar\nowidctlpar\sl360\slmult1\par
\pard\ltrpar\keepn\s3\sb240\sa60\ul COMPOUNDING \par
\pard\ltrpar\sa200\sl360\slmult1\ulnone  Two forms of treatment of interest are possible. In the case of \b Simple interest\b0 , interest is paid (earned) only on the original amount (principal) borrowed. In the case of \b Compound interest\b0 , interest is paid (earned) on any previous interest earned as well as on the principal borrowed (lent). Compound interest is crucial to the understanding of the mathematics of finance. In most situations involving the time value of money compounding of interest is assumed. The \b future value\b0  of present amount is found by applying compound interest over a specified period of time \par
\pard\ltrpar\s7\sb240\sa60\sl360\slmult1 The Equation for finding future values of a single amount is derived as follows:\par
\pard\ltrpar\sa200\sl360\slmult1\qj Let  FV\sub n\nosupersub  = future value at the end of period n \par
      PV (P\sub o\nosupersub ) =Initial principal, or present value \par
      k= annual rate of interest\par
      n = number of periods the money is left on deposit.\par
The future value (FV), or compound value, of a present amount, Po, is found as follows.\par
At end of Year 1, FV\sub 1\tab\nosupersub =P\sub o \nosupersub (1+k)                                               = Po (1+k)\super 1\nosupersub\par
At end of Year 2\sub ,\nosupersub   FV\sub 2\nosupersub\tab =FV\sub 1\nosupersub  (1+k) = P\sub o\nosupersub (1+k) (1+k)                    = Po ( 1+k)\super 2\nosupersub\par
At end of Year 3,  FV\sub 3    \nosupersub  = FV\sub 2\nosupersub  (1+k) = Po ( 1+k) ( 1+k) (1+k)    = Po (1+k)\super 3\par
\nosupersub A general equation for the future value at end of \i n\i0  periods can therefore be formulated as,\par
\trowd\trgaph108\trleft-108\trrh530\trpaddl108\trpaddr108\trpaddfl3\trpaddfr3
\clbrdrl\brdrw15\brdrs\brdrcf2\clbrdrt\brdrw15\brdrs\brdrcf2\clbrdrr\brdrw15\brdrs\brdrcf2\clbrdrb\brdrw15\brdrs\brdrcf2 \cellx9434\pard\intbl\ltrpar\sa200\sl360\slmult1\qj\b FV\sub n\nosupersub  = Po ( 1+k)\super n\nosupersub\b0\cell\row\pard\ltrpar\nowidctlpar\sl360\slmult1\par
\b Example\b0 :\par
Assume that you have just invested Ksh100, 000. The investment is expected to earn interest at a rate of 20% compounded annually. Determine the future value of the investment after 3 years.\par
 Solution:\par
\pard\ltrpar\sa200\sl360\slmult1\qj At end of Year 1, FV\sub 1\tab\nosupersub =100,000\sub  \nosupersub (1+0.2) =120,000                                              \par
At end of Year 2\sub ,\nosupersub  FV\sub 2\nosupersub\tab =120,000 (1+0.2) OR \{ 100,000(1+0.2) (1+0.2)\}=144,000\par
At end of Year 3, FV\sub 3    \nosupersub  = 144,000(1+0.2) =100,000 ( 1+0.2) ( 1+0.2) (1+0.2)    = 172,800\par
\pard\ltrpar\nowidctlpar\sl360\slmult1\tx3000 Alternatively,\par
\par
\pard\ltrpar\sa200\sl360\slmult1\qj At the end of 3 years, FV\sub 3\nosupersub  = 100,000 ( 1+0.2)\super 3    \nosupersub = Sh.172,800\par
\b Using Tables to Find Future Values\par
\b0 Unless you have financial calculator at hand, solving for future values using the above equation  can be quite time consuming because you will have to raise (1+k) to the \b\i n\b0\i0 th power. \par
Thus we introduce tables giving values of (1+k)\super n\nosupersub  for various values of \i k \i0 and\i  n. \i0 Table A-3  at the back of this book contains a set of these interest rate tables. Table A-3 \b Future Value of $1 at the End of n Periods\b0 1 gives the \b future value interest factors. \b0 These factors are the multipliers used to calculate at a specified interest rate the future values of a present amount as of a given date. The future value interest factor for an initial investment of Sh.1 compounded at \i k \i0 percent for \i n \i0 periods is referred to as FVIF\sub k n. \par
\pard\ltrpar\li720\sa200\sl360\slmult1\qj\nosupersub\b             Future value interest factors = FVIF\sub k n. \nosupersub = (1+k)\super n\nosupersub\b0  .                           \b\par
\b0\tab\b FV\sub n\nosupersub  = Po * FVIF\sub k,n\nosupersub  \super    \nosupersub                                                     \par
\pard\ltrpar\sa200\sl360\slmult1\qj\b0 A general equation for the future value at end of \i n\i0  periods using tables can therefore be formulated as,\par
\trowd\trgaph108\trleft-108\trrh530\trpaddl108\trpaddr108\trpaddfl3\trpaddfr3
\clbrdrl\brdrw15\brdrs\brdrcf2\clbrdrt\brdrw15\brdrs\brdrcf2\clbrdrr\brdrw15\brdrs\brdrcf2\clbrdrb\brdrw15\brdrs\brdrcf2 \cellx9434\pard\intbl\ltrpar\sa200\sl360\slmult1\qj\b FV\sub n\nosupersub  = Po\'d7 FVIF\sub k,n\nosupersub  \super    \nosupersub                                                    \b0\cell\row\pard\ltrpar\li720\sa200\sl360\slmult1\qj\b                       \b0\tab\b\par
\pard\ltrpar\sa200\sl360\slmult1\qj\b0 The FVIF for an initial principal of Sh.1 compounded at  k percent for n periods can be found in Appendix Table A-3 by looking for the intersection of the \i n\i0 th row an the \i k \i0 % column. A future value interest factor is the multiplier used to calculate at the specified rate the future value of a present amount as of a given date. \par
From the example above,\par
\b FV\sub 3\nosupersub  = 100,000 \'d7 FVIF\sub 20%,3 years\nosupersub  \super    \nosupersub                                                    \b0\par
\pard\ltrpar\nowidctlpar\sl360\slmult1\tx3000         =100,000 \'d7 1.7280\par
        =sh.172, 800\par
\b Future value of an annuity\par
\pard\ltrpar\sa200\sl360\slmult1\qj\b0 So far we have been looking at the future value of a simple, single amount which grows over a given period at a given rate. We will now consider annuities.\par
 An \b annuity\b0  is a series of payments or receipts of equal amounts (i.e. a pensioner receiving Sh.100,000 per year for ten years after his retirement). The two basic types of annuities are the \b ordinary annuity \b0 and the \b annuity due. \b0 An \i ordinary annuity\i0  is an annuity where the cash flow occurs at the end of each period. In an \i annuity due\i0  the cash flows occur at the beginning of each period. This means that cash flows are sooner received with an annuity due than for a similar ordinary annuity. Consequently, the future value of an annuity due is higher than that of an ordinary annuity because the annuity due\rquote s cash flows earn interest for one more year.\par
\pard\ltrpar\nowidctlpar\sl360\slmult1\tx3000\b Example:\par
\b0 Determine the future value of a shs100, 000 investment made \i at the end\i0  of every year for 5 years assume the required rate of return is 12% compounded annually.\par
\b Solution.\par
\pard\ltrpar\sa200\sl360\slmult1\qj\b0 The future value interest factor for an n-year, k%, ordinary annuity (FVIFA) can be found by adding the sum of the first n-1 FVIFs to 1.000, as follows;\b\par
