Compounding More Frequently. \par
\ulnone\b0  Interest is often compounded more frequently than once a year. Financial institutions compound interest semi-annually, quarterly, monthly, weekly, daily or even continuously. \par
\b Semi Annual Compounding \par
\b0 This involves the compounding of interest over two periods of six months each within a year. Instead of stated interest rate being paid once a year one half of the stated interest is paid twice a year.. \par
\pard\ltrpar\s7\sb240\sa60\b Example\par
\pard\ltrpar\sa200\qj\b0 Sharon decided to invest Sh.100,000 in savings account paying 8% interest compounded semi annually. If she leaves the money in the account for 2 years how much will she have at the end of the two years?\par
She will be paid 4% interest for each 6-months period. Thus her money will amount to.\par
\pard\ltrpar\li720\sa200\qj\par
\tab FV\sub 4\nosupersub\tab =\tab 100,000 ( 1+.08/2)\super 2*2 \nosupersub =100,000(1+.04)\super 4\nosupersub\tab =Sh.116,990\par
           Or\par
\tab Using tables = 100,000 x FVIF\sub  4%,4periods\nosupersub\b  \super   \nosupersub        =\b0 100,000 x 1.17 = Sh.117,000\par
\par
\pard\ltrpar\sa200\qj\b Quarterly Compounding\par
\b0 This involves\b  \b0 compounding of interest over four periods of three months each at one fourth of stated annual interest rate.\b  \par
Example\par
\pard\ltrpar\qj\b0 Suppose Jane found an institution that will pay her 8% interest compounded quarterly. How much will she have in the account at the end of 2 years?\par
\pard\ltrpar\li1440\sa200\qj FV\sub 8\nosupersub  = 100,000(1+.08/4)\super 4*2\nosupersub =100,000(1+.02)\super 8 \nosupersub =100,000 x 1.1716 =      117,160\par
\pard\ltrpar\li720\sa200\qj Or,\par
\tab Using tables 100,000 x FVIF\sub  2%,8periods\nosupersub\b   = \b0 100,000\b *\b0 1.172 = 117,200\par
\pard\ltrpar\sa200\qj As shown by the calculations in the two preceding examples of semi-annual and quarterly compounding, the more frequently interest is compounded ,the greater the rate of growth of an initial deposit. This holds for any interest rate and any period.\par
