\pard\ltrpar\sa200\qj\b   Continuous Compounding. \par
\pard\ltrpar\qj\b0 This involves compounding of interest an infinite number of times per year, at intervals of microseconds - the smallest time period imaginable. In this case m approaches infinity and through calculus the Future Value equation 2.1 would become,\b               \par
 FV\sub n\nosupersub  (continuous compounding)   = Po x  e \super k x n             \tab\tab\tab\nosupersub (2.5)\b0\par
\pard\ltrpar\sa200\qj  Where e is the exponential function, which has a value of 2.7183. The FVIFk,n (continuous compounding) is therefore  e\super kn \nosupersub , which can be found on calculators.\par
\pard\ltrpar\s7\sb240\sa60 Example\par
\pard\ltrpar\sa200\qj If Jane deposited her 100,000/= in an institution that pays 8% compounded continuously, what would be the amount on the account after 2 years?\par
 Amount = 100,000 x 2.718\super .08*2\nosupersub  = 100,000 x 2.718\super 0.16   \nosupersub =100,000*1.1735 =117,350\par
