Table A - 2 \b Present Value of an Annuity \b0 provides the PVIFA\sub k,n, \nosupersub which can be used in calculating the present value of an annuity (PVA) as follows:\par
\trowd\trgaph108\trleft-108\trrh468\trpaddl108\trpaddr108\trpaddfl3\trpaddfr3
\clbrdrl\brdrw15\brdrs\brdrcf2\clbrdrt\brdrw15\brdrs\brdrcf2\clbrdrr\brdrw15\brdrs\brdrcf2\clbrdrb\brdrw15\brdrs\brdrcf2 \cellx9384\pard\intbl\ltrpar\nowidctlpar\sl360\slmult1\tx3000\b PVA    =   PMT \'d7 PVIFA\sub k n \nosupersub                                                                         \cell\row\pard\ltrpar\sa200\sl360\slmult1\qj Example\par
\b0  Assume that a project will give you sh. 1000 at the end of each year for 4 years .What is the maximum amount would you be willing to pay for that project if the required rate of return is 10%.\par
\b Solution \par
\b0 The PVIFA at 10% for 4 years (PVIFA\sub 10%,4yrs\nosupersub ) from Table A-2  is 3.1699. \par
Therefore, PVA = 3.1699X 1000 = \b Sh.3, 169.9\par
\b0 (Confirm the answer with the above equation).\par
\b\par
Present Value of an Annuity Due.\par
\b0 From the above example, assume that the project gives you sh. 1000 \i at the beginning\i0  of each year for 4 years.\par
PVIFA\sub k,n\nosupersub (annuity due) = PVIF\sub k,n\nosupersub (ordinary annuity) x ( 1 +k)\par
\b                                    = \b0 3.1699 \'d7 (1+0.1)\b\par
\b0                                   =3.48689\par
Therefore future value of the annuity due   = 1000 x 3.48689\par
                                  \b =Sh.3, 486.89\par
Present Value of Perpetuity\par
\b0 Perpetuity is an annuity with an infinite life \endash  never stops producing a cash flow at the end of each year forever. \par
The PVIF for a perpetuity discounted at the rate k is \par
\tab\tab\tab\b PVIFA\sub k, \f3\'e1\f0  \tab\nosupersub =\tab 1/k\par
\pard\ltrpar\s7\sb240\sa60\sl360\slmult1 Example \par
\pard\ltrpar\sa200\sl360\slmult1\qj\b0 Wetika wishes to determine the PV of a Sh.1000 perpetuity discounted at 10%.\par
The present value of the perpetuity is 1000 x PVIFA\sub k, \f3\'e1\nosupersub\f0  = 1000 x 1/0.1= Sh.10, 000.\par
This implies that the receipt of Sh.1,000 for an indefinite period is worth only Sh .10,000 today if Wetika can earn 10% on her investments (If she had Sh.10,000 and earned 10% interest on it each year, she could  withdraw Sh.1000  annually without touching the initial Sh.10,000).\par
\pard\ltrpar\sa200\qj\b Deposits to Accumulate a Future Sum. \par
\b0  It may be necessary to find out the periodic deposits that should lead to the built of a needed sum of money in future. \par
\pard\ltrpar\sa200\qj\tx7560 We can use the expression below, which is a rewriting of \b FV\sub n\nosupersub  = Po \'d7 FVIF\sub k,n\nosupersub\b0 .\tab\par
\pard\ltrpar\sa200\qj\b        PMT \tab =\tab FVA\sub n\nosupersub /FVIFA\sub k n\b0                                                     \nosupersub  \par
Where PMT is the periodic deposit, FVA\sub n \nosupersub is the future sum to be accumulated, and FVIFA\sub k n \nosupersub is the future value interest factor of an n-year annuity discounted at k%.\par
\pard\ltrpar\s7\sb240\sa60\b Example\par
\pard\ltrpar\sa200\qj\b0 Ben needs to accumulate Sh. 5 million at the end of 5 years to purchase a company. He can make deposits in an account that pays 10% interest compounded annually. How much should he deposit in his account annually to accumulate this sum? \par
\b Solution\par
PMT = FVA\sub n\nosupersub /FVIFA\sub k n     =         \nosupersub 5,000,000/6.105\tab =\tab Sh.819,000\par
\pard\ltrpar\s7\sb240\sa60 Example\par
\pard\ltrpar\sa200\qj\b0 Suppose you want to buy a house in 5 years from now and estimate that the initial down payment of Sh. 2 million will be required at that time. You wish to make equal annual end of year deposits in an account paying annual interest of 6%. Determine the size of the annual deposit. \par
\par
FVA\sub N\nosupersub  = PMT X FVIFA\sub K, N \par
\nosupersub PMT =\tab  FVAn/\sub  \nosupersub FVIFA\sub k n \par
\ul\par
\ulnone\nosupersub\b PMT = 2,000,000/5.637=    Sh.354,799\par
