\pard\ltrpar\keepn\s1\sl360\slmult1\lang2057 COST OF CAPITAL\par
\pard\ltrpar\keepn\s2\sb240\sa60\sl276\slmult1\lang1033\ulnone Objectives\par
\pard\ltrpar\sa200\sl276\slmult1\b0 At the end of the chapter you should be conversant with:\par
1. Meaning and application of cost of capital.\par
2. Computation of specific cost of capital.\par
3. Weighted average cost of capital (WACC) and weighted marginal cost of capital (WMCC)\par
4. Term structure of interest rates.\par
\pard\ltrpar\nowidctlpar\sl360\slmult1\tx3000\ul\b\par
\par
\pard\ltrpar\keepn\s2\sb240\sa60\sl276\slmult1 Introduction.\par
\pard\ltrpar\nowidctlpar\sl360\slmult1\tx3000\ulnone\b0 The cost of capital of a project is the minimum required rate of return expected on funds committed to the project. It is the required rate of return by the providers of funds.\par
\ul Significance of cost of capital\b\par
\ulnone\b0 a) It is useful in long term investment decisions so as to determine which project should be undertaken. The techniques used to make this decision include net present value and IRR.\par
b) It is also used in capital structure decisions to determine the mix of various components in the capital structure. The cost of capital of each component is determined.\par
c) Used for performance appraisal. A high cost of capital is an indicator of high risk attached to the firm usually attributed to the performance of the management of a firm\par
d) In making lease or buy decisions. In lease or buy decisions the cost of debt is used as the discounting rate.\par
\par
\pard\ltrpar\keepn\s3\sb240\sa60\ul SPECIFIC COSTS OF CAPITAL \ulnone\par
\pard\ltrpar\nowidctlpar\sl360\slmult1\tx3000 Specific costs of capital are the costs of capital of each source of capital such as debt, preference shares and equity.\par
\b a) Cost of debt (kd)\b0\par
The cost of debt for a perpetual debenture will be;\par
          K\sub d \nosupersub   = \ul   I  \par
\ulnone                       P\sub b\nosupersub\par
I     is the annual interest\par
P\sub b    \nosupersub  is the current market value of a debenture\par
\par
If the debenture is redeemable after a certain period of time/it has a maturity period the following formula will be applied to get the cost of debt or yield to maturity;\par
\par
k\sub d\nosupersub    =   I   +  \ul M   -P\sub b\nosupersub\par
\ulnone             \ul              n         \par
\ulnone                    \ul M   + P\sub b\ulnone\nosupersub\par
                         2\par
I  is the annual interest\par
M  is the par value of the debenture\par
P\sub b\nosupersub   is the current market value of the debenture\par
n   is the period to maturity\par
The above formula gives the pre-tax cost of debt the after tax cost of debt for which interest paid on debentures is an allowable expense for tax purposes will therefore be;\par
K\sub d\nosupersub   (1-T)   T being the tax rate.\par
\par
\b b) Cost of preference shares (k\sub p\nosupersub )\b0\par
The required return to the preference shareholders with perpetual preference share capital will be;\par
K\sub p\nosupersub  =   \ul d\sub p\nosupersub     \par
\ulnone             P\sub p\nosupersub\par
d\sub p\nosupersub   is the preference dividend per share\par
P\sub p\nosupersub   is the market price per preference share\par
Where the company incurred floatation cost the kp   = \ul dp   \par
\ulnone                                                                                      P\sub p\nosupersub -Fc\par
Fc   is the floatation cost\par
\par
\b c) Cost of ordinary shares/equity (k\sub e\nosupersub )\par
\b0 Equity can be either internally generated (from retained earnings) or externally generated (the common share capital).\par
The cost of retained earnings (k\sub r\nosupersub ). Retained earnings are an internal financing received without incurring floatation costs. It can be calculated as follows;\par
\par
\par
k\sub r \nosupersub   = \ul d\sub 1 \nosupersub  \ulnone   +  g\par
         P\sub o\nosupersub\par
The cost of external equity (k\sub s\nosupersub ) can be calculated as follows;\par
\par
k\sub s\nosupersub    =\ul   d\sub 1\nosupersub      \ulnone +    g\par
         P\sub 0\nosupersub  -Fc\par
Where Fc is the floatation cost which may be given as the percentage of the price or in shilling value.\par
\par
\b Weighted average cost of capital (WACC)\par
\b0 This is the overall/composite cost of capital that a firm is currently using. It is calculated by determining the weighted average cost of each source of capital in the firm\rquote s capital structure.\par
\par
WACC(k\sub o\nosupersub ) = k\sub d\nosupersub ( \ul D\ulnone  )  +  k\sub p\nosupersub  ( \ul P\ulnone  )   +   k\sub r\nosupersub  ( \ul R \ulnone )   +  k\sub s\nosupersub  ( \ul S \ulnone )\ul\b\par
\ulnone\b0                            V                V                V                V\par
\par
Where;\par
\b k\sub d\nosupersub , k\sub p\nosupersub , k\sub r\nosupersub , k\sub s   \nosupersub\b0  =percentage cost of debt, preference share capital, retained earnings and external equity respectively\par
D, P, R, S      =total debt, preference, retained and ordinary share capital respectively\par
V=          total value/capital of the firm\par
Hence, \ul D\ulnone ,   \ul P,\ulnone    \ul R,\ulnone    \ul S \ulnone   are the proportions or weights of debt, preference capital, retained \par
             V   V    V   V earnings and external equity in the capital structure respectively\par
\b Example.\par
\b0 Bahati Company has the following capital structure.\par
\par
Source            \tab  amount\par
Debentures         \tab  8,000,000\par
Preference capital   \tab 2,000,000\par
Retained earnings   \tab 4,000,000\par
Ordinary share capital \tab\ul 6,000,000\par
\ulnone                               20,000,000\par
The component costs of capital are; kd is 6%, kp is10.5%, kr is 14%,ks is 17.2%\par
Compute the WACC.\par
K\sub o \nosupersub =  w\sub d\nosupersub k\sub d\nosupersub +  w\sub p\nosupersub k\sub p\nosupersub  + w\sub r\nosupersub k\sub r \nosupersub + w\sub s\nosupersub k\sub s\nosupersub\par
\pard\ltrpar\nowidctlpar\sl360\slmult1\par
The w\sub d\nosupersub ,w\sub p\nosupersub ,w\sub r\nosupersub ,w\sub s\nosupersub    are the weights of the specific sources of capital whose sum is 1.\par
k\sub o \nosupersub = 6 (\ul  8m\ulnone ) + 10.5( \ul 2m \ulnone ) +14( \ul 4m\ulnone ) +17.2 ( \ul 6m\ulnone )\b\par
\b0             20m             20m          20m            20m\par
\par
\b Ko = 11.41%\par
\b0 The weighted average cost of capital can be used to evaluate the performance of management. Since it is a historic cost it is not useful in investment decisions as it is irrelevant. In making decisions the future costs are considered and hence the need for the marginal cost of capital (MCC).\par
Marginal cost of capital (MCC)\par
This is the cost of raising an additional shilling. It considers the cost of raising additional or future financing. An increase in the level of financing increases the cost of various types of finances. As retained earnings are exhausted there may be a need to issue new ordinary shares which comes with high floatation costs hence a higher marginal cost of capital.\par
\par
\b Example.\par
\b0 Mina ltd has 300,000 of retained earnings available. The kr is 13%. If the company exhausts the retained earnings it can issue equity whose cost is 14%. The firm expects that it can borrow up to 400,000 at 5.6%, beyond that additional debt will have an after tax cost of 8.4%\par
Unlimited amounts of funds can be raised by issuing preference stock at a current cost of 10.6%.Mina  Ltds capital structure is 40% debt, 50% equity,10% preference.\par
Calculate the marginal cost of capital of the various ranges of total financing.\par
The \b Break point \b0 reflects the level of total new financing at which the cost of one of the financing components rises.\par
BPj  = \ul AF\par
\ulnone             Wj\par
Where; AF is the amount of funds available from source j at a given cost before braking point.\par
         Wj is the capital structure weight of source j\par
BP of equity = \ul 300,000 \ulnone   = 600,000\par
                 0.5\par
BP of debt = \ul 400,000 \ulnone    = 1,000,000\par
                0.4\par
      Breaking point                                 MCC\par
\pard{\pntext\f0 1\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlbody\pnf0\pnindent360\pnstart1\pndec }
\ltrpar\nowidctlpar\fi-360\li720\sl360\slmult1         600,000                 0.4(5.6)+ 0.1(10.6) +0.5(13) = 9.8%\par
\pard\ltrpar\nowidctlpar\sl360\slmult1     600,001-   1,000,000                 0.4(5.6) + 0.1(10.6) + 0.5(14)=10.8%\par
              Over 1m                         0.4(8.4) +0.1(10.6) + 0.5(14)=11.5%\par
Preference share capital cost does not change with the breaking points as we are told we can raise unlimited funds at the same cost. The retained earnings are exhausted at the 600,001 shilling so the cost increases as new equity is issued at 14%.\par
The \b marginal cost of capital schedule \b0 shows the relationship between the MCC and the amount of funds raised by the company.\par
\b Weaknesses of WACC as a discounting rate.\par
\pard{\pntext\f0 1\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlbody\pnf0\pnindent360\pnstart1\pndec }
\ltrpar\nowidctlpar\fi-360\li720\sl360\slmult1\b0 It is an historical cost and therefore would not be appropriate t use in investments decision as only future cash flows should be used. When calculating cost of equity the dividend is used and so is the growth rate which is gotten from past stream of dividends.\par
\pard{\pntext\f0 2\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlbody\pnf0\pnindent360\pnstart2\pndec }
\ltrpar\nowidctlpar\fi-360\li720\sl360\slmult1 It assumes that the capital structure is optimal which is not achievable in the real world.\par
\pard{\pntext\f0 3\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlbody\pnf0\pnindent360\pnstart3\pndec }
\ltrpar\nowidctlpar\fi-360\li720\sl360\slmult1 It can only be use das a discounting rate assuming that the risk of the project is equal to the business risk of the firm. if the project has higher risk then a percentage premium will be added to WACC to determine the appropriate discounting rate.\par
\pard\ltrpar\nowidctlpar\li360\sl360\slmult1\par
\pard\ltrpar\nowidctlpar\sl360\slmult1\b WEIGHTED MARGINAL COST OF CAPITAL (WMCC) SCHEDULE.\par
\b0 This is a schedule that shows the relationship between the marginal cost of capital; and the amount of funds raise d by a company. The marginal cost of capital can either be constant or have breaks or breaking points.\par
\par
\par
\par
 \par
\lang1089 cost                                                                         Cost\lang1033\par
\par
\par
\par
\par
\par
\par
          K\sub d \nosupersub K\sub p\nosupersub K\sub r \nosupersub and K\sub s  \nosupersub are constant.\par
                                                                 Amount\par
                                                                                                                                   \par
             \b Constant                                                                              Breaking points.\par
\par
\b0\par
Constant cost of capital schedule occurs if it is possible to raise a limited amount of funds from each of the sources at the same cost. A breaking point MCC occurs if additional funds from any of the sources can only be raised at a higher cost. The most common  MCC schedule is one with a break when retained earnings are exhausted.\par
\par
Breaking Point = \ul Total cheaper funds from a given source \ulnone  \par
                             Proportion of that source in the capital structure.\par
