Term structure of interest rates.\par
\b0 The term structure of interest rates describes the relationship between interest rates and the term to maturity and the differences between the short term and long term interest rates.\par
Theories which have been advanced to explain the nature if he yield curve \endash which is a graph of the term structure of interest rates depicting the relationship between yield to maturity of a security-on the y-axis and the time to maturity-on the x-axis.\par
\par
\b Theories of term structure.\par
\pard\ltrpar\nowidctlpar\fi-360\li810\sl360\slmult1\b0 1.\tab\b Liquidity preference theory\b0 .\par
\pard\ltrpar\nowidctlpar\sl360\slmult1 This theory states that short term bonds are more favourable than long term bonds because;\par
Investors perceive less risk in short term securities because they are more liquid. Hence they can accept lower yields to avoid the risk.\par
Borrowers on the other hand, will prefer longer tem bonds so as to delay repayment of the debt. They are thus willing too pay a higher rate for longer term bonds.\par
These preferences result in a premium being paid which increases as the time to maturity increases. Hence this explains an upward sloping yield curve.\par
\pard\ltrpar\nowidctlpar\fi-360\li810\sl360\slmult1\b 2.\tab\b0  \b Expectations hypothesis\par
\pard\ltrpar\nowidctlpar\sl360\slmult1\b0 This theory states that the yield curve depends on the expectations about the future inflation rate. If the inflation rate is expected to rise, then the rate on long term bonds will exceed that of short term loan. In this case the yield curve would be upward sloping, the reverse is true. The expected future interest rates are equal to forward rates computed from the expectations with regard to the future interest rates.\par
The following conditions are necessary for the expectations hypothesis to hold;\par
\pard{\pntext\f0 1\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlbody\pnf0\pnindent360\pnstart1\pndec }
\ltrpar\nowidctlpar\fi-360\li1440\sl360\slmult1 There\rquote s a perfect capital market with many buyers and sellers.\par
\pard{\pntext\f0 2\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlbody\pnf0\pnindent360\pnstart2\pndec }
\ltrpar\nowidctlpar\fi-360\li1440\sl360\slmult1 Investors are assumed to be rational. Are wealth maximizes\par
\pard{\pntext\f0 3\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlbody\pnf0\pnindent360\pnstart3\pndec }
\ltrpar\nowidctlpar\fi-360\li1440\sl360\slmult1 Investors have homogeneous expectations about future interest rates and return on investment.\par
\pard{\pntext\f0 4\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlbody\pnf0\pnindent360\pnstart4\pndec }
\ltrpar\nowidctlpar\fi-360\li1440\sl360\slmult1 The bankruptcy of firms due to the use of borrowing is unlikely.\par
\pard{\*\pn\pnlvlcont\pnf0\pnindent0\pnstart1\pndec }
\ltrpar\nowidctlpar\fi-360\li810\sl360\slmult1\b 3.\tab Market segmentation theory \par
\pard\ltrpar\nowidctlpar\sl360\slmult1\b0 It state that the market for loans is segmented on the basis of maturity and are confined to a segment of the market and will not change even if the forecast of the likely future interest changes.\par
The supply and demand for loans in each segment will determine the prevailing rates in that segment. Take an example of someone borrowing to build a house they would most likely prefer a long term loan. The lower rates say in the short term segment and high rates in the long term segment would result in an upward sloping curve\par
\par
