\pard\ltrpar\sa200\sl276\slmult1 Change in networking capital (NWC) Net working capital is the difference between current assets (CA) and current liabilities (CL) i.e. NWC  = CA \endash CL. Changes in NWC often accompany capital expenditure decisions. If a company acquires a new machinery to expand its levels of operation, levels of cash, accounts receivables, inventories, accounts payable, accruals will increase. Increases in current assets are uses of cash while increases in current liabilities are sources of cash. As long as the expanded operations continue, the increased investment in current assets (cash, accounts receivables and inventory) and increased current liabilities (accounts payables and accruals) would be expected to continue.\par
\pard\ltrpar\sa200\sl360\slmult1 Generally, current assets increase by more than the increase in current liabilities, resulting in an increase in NWC which would be treated as an initial outflow (This is an internal build up of accounts with no tax implications, and a tax adjustment is therefore unnecessary).\par
